post_text:
Dear Incoming Families,

We are so excited to welcome to the Sunapee Central Elementary Kindergarten program. In the past, we held our screening process in the spring but due to COVID-19, we moved it to the end of the summer to Thursday, August 20, 2020 starting at 9:00 am at SCES. When you and your child come, we have a number of activities for both of you to participate so everyone is ready to start school on Monday, August 31st. It will take approximately 40 minutes to complete this informal screening. Below you will find a link to a Sign-Up Genius page so you can sign up for a time. Unfortunately, due to timing, we are unable to offer another date or time. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact me at either 763-5675 or at whuston@sunapeeschools.org.

Thanks and we look forward to seeing you on August 20th!!

The link to the Sign Up Genius is:

https://www.signupgenius.com/go/10C0D4DAAA72FA4FDC34-kindergarten

If the link does not work, you will need to copy and paste it into your search engine bar.

post_text: Here is information from the Sunapee Police Benevolent Association regarding Friday's graduation parade!
shared_text:
Sunapee Police Benevolent Association
May 27 at 6:16 PM Â·

To celebrate the upcoming graduation of the Sunapee Middle High School Class of 2020, SMHS, The Sunapee Police Department, the Sunapee Fire Department, and members of the community will be holding a celebratory parade through town on:

Friday, June 5th at approximately 7:30pm!

The parade route will be as follows:

-Route 11 from the junction of 103B
-Right on to Central Street
-Left on Main Street into Sunapee Harbor
-Right on to River Road
-Left on Main Street toward Route 11
-Straight on to Lower Main Street
-The conclusion of the parade will be at the intersection of Lower Main Street and North Road

**The parade should disperse from here**

While we encourage everyone to come out and support our graduating senior class, please remember to practice social distancing along the entire parade route!

Congratulations Senior Class of 2020!

post_text:
The Sunapee Push up challenge did not make its goal, but a lot of kids sure got stronger each day! The challenge finished up with just under 21,000 push ups for the week. Some of the students did over 100 a day!! A lot of kids really crushed the challenge and we had some great Hang Outs of push up mania. We may try this again and we will really look to beat 21,000 and maybe even get to the elusive 100,000 mark.

Hi Mrs. Cruz! Idid 31 push ups today! That's the most I've done all weak! I LOVE LOVE LOVE LOVE this push up thing!!!!!!!!
Thanks for keeping me strong!!
~ Ava S.

post_text:
Dear Sunapee Families,

As we head into the second full week of remote learning, please know that we are thinking of you and hoping that your family is well. We recognize and applaud you for the time and support you've provided to ensure that remote learning for your child(ren) is successful. At this time we are seeking your feedback to determine how best to problem solve challenges, recognize successes, and provide ongoing support. We hope that you will take a minute to complete the short survey that has been sent to your email address. We ask that you complete a separate survey for each child.

Thank you,

Russ

The Sunapee School District will have an early release tomorrow (Tuesday February 18th) due to the predicted inclement weather. School will be dismissed at 12:00. Please make arrangements for your child to either arrive home early through the bus system, or to be picked up at school at 12:00. If you would like to make arrangements outside of your normal school day plan, please send your student with a note describing the plan.

The afternoon career and technical education classes have been cancelled as have all afternoon co-curricular events. As a result of the early dismissal there will be no preschool program tomorrow.

If a cancellation is deemed necessary a morning announcement will be made to alert you to the change.

post_text:
Dear Sunapee Community Members,

The Sunapee School District is holding its fourth public community forum on Wednesday,
December 11, 2019 at 6pm at the Sunapee Middle High School Gymnasium. This will be the
final community forum before the January budget hearing, February deliberative session
and March voting.

At the October 30th forum Banwell Architects discussed two different proposals to address
the one-site option: one with an auditorium and one without. The December 11th forum will
present the modified building plan for a PreK-12 one-site facility as well as the plan for the
district sports fields. A revised cost estimation will also be given.

Because of your strong interest in the Sunapee community, we would like to personally
invite you to the December 11th forum to see the plans which are being prepared for the
March, 2020 warrant.

There will be childcare provided by the Sunapee National Honor Society students from
5:45pm to 8pm. We hope you will join us for this very important meeting.
Sincerely,

Russell E. Holden
Superintendent

post_text:
As you may be aware, the Sunapee School District is actively looking into district-wide capital facility improvements. A third public community forum is planned for Wednesday, October 30, 2019 at 6m at the Sunapee Middle High School to present progress to date and to hear community input.

At the September 12th forum Banwell Architects presented several different proposals to address our facility needs. Based on feedback from the sizeable turn out at that forum, a one-site option was favored and more detailed plans are being designed by the architects for presentation at the October 30th forum. There will also be a cost estimation for the project presented at this time.

Because of your strong interest in the Sunapee community we would like to personally invite you to the October 30th forum so that you can share and hear the ideas of others in the community.

There will be childcare provided by the Sunapee National Honor Society students from 5:45pm to 8pm. We hope you will join us for this very important meeting.

Sincerely,

Russell E. Holden

Superintendent

The Sunapee School Board Capital Improvement Projects (CIP) Subcommittee has been making good progress with leveraging community input for our district building project. For the next Community Forum at the Sunapee Middle High School on October 30th at 6:00PM, we will have new plans, information and cost estimates to share. Onsite babysitting will be available.

As we continue to work on this project, we are seeking community input for solutions for our athletic fields space requirements. We are looking for 6-10 acres of land that would be available in town that is relatively flat and accessible. Please contact Superintendent Russ Holden (rholden@sunapeeschools.org) with any possible solutions. To find out more visit www.sau85.org and click on the Capital Improvements Projects page.

Sunapee Middle High Schoolâ€™s Annual Bartlett Prize Speaking Contest
Seventy-seven years after the Honorable John H. Bartlett (Governor of NH 1919 â€“ 1921) established a prize speaking program in Sunapee for school children; students continue to present their memorized pieces in this annual contest which will be held at 7:00pm on June 6, 2019 at Sunapee Middle High School.

Students will be judged on the following: interpretation, poise, diction, voice, memorization and the difficulty of the piece.

All are welcome

post_text: Sunapee High School will be conducting the annual Center for Disease Control Youth Risk Behavior Survey on June 4th to all students in grades 9-12. The survey will ask about the health behaviors of 9th through 12th grade students. The survey will ask about nutrition, physical activity, injuries, and tobacco, alcohol, and other drug use. It will also ask about sexual behaviors that could lead to pregnancy and sexually transmitted diseases, including HIV. Students will be asked to fill out a survey that takes about 45 minutes to complete. For the survey results to be accurate, it is important that all students, regardless of whether they have engaged in health-risk behaviors, are given an opportunity to participate in the survey, but the survey is voluntary. A copy of the Survey is available in the front office at SMHS for your review.

post_text:
Thanks to the Sunapee Police Benevolent Association for putting this assembly on.
---
Alcohol Awareness Week 2019: Pictured here, a group of Sunapee firefighters are preparing to remove the roof of the vehicle to extricate a driver during Sunapee Middle High School alcohol awareness week. The other photo shows Lt. Cobb talking about the dangers of underage drinking and the criminal penalties of DWI, underage possession and negligent homicide.

The Sunapee Police, Sunapee Fire and the school staff all enjoyed taking part and supporting the students while they prepare and present their programs during the week.

Great job!
